\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 2: 
\series default
Now we will show that any injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map out of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 splits.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to M$
\end_inset

 be any injective 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to M$
\end_inset

 splits if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\varphi(E)\to M$
\end_inset

 splits, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

 denotes the inclusion map.
 Indeed, denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}\colon E\to\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

 to be the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to M$
\end_inset

 splits, then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\varphi=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\widetilde{\varphi}\colon M\to\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

 splits 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\varphi(E)\to M$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi\widetilde{\varphi}\iota)(\varphi(u)) & =\varphi\widetilde{\varphi}(\varphi(u))\\
 & =\varphi(\widetilde{\varphi}\varphi(u))\\
 & =\varphi(u)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(u)\in\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\varphi(E)\to M$
\end_inset

 splits, then there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}\colon M\to\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\iota}\iota=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{-1}\widetilde{\iota}\colon M\to E$
\end_inset

 splits 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to M$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\varphi^{-1}\widetilde{\iota}\varphi)(u) & =(\varphi^{-1}\widetilde{\iota})(\varphi(u))\\
 & =(\varphi^{-1}\widetilde{\iota})(\iota\varphi(u))\\
 & =(\varphi^{-1}\widetilde{\iota}\iota)(\varphi(u))\\
 & =(\varphi^{-1})(\varphi(u))\\
 & =u
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus, to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon E\to M$
\end_inset

 splits, it suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\varphi(E)\to M$
\end_inset

 splits.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

 is a submodule of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, and by step 1, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is an internal direct sum, say
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\varphi(E)\oplus K
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq M$
\end_inset

.
 The projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}\colon M\to\varphi(E)$
\end_inset

 is easily seen to split the inclusion map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon\varphi(E)\to M$
\end_inset

.
 
